06235nam a22009375i 9780812294804DE-B159720180924034856.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||180924s2018    pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808122948047 a10.9783/97808122948042doi  a(DE-B1597)494838  a(OCoLC)1027476986  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA04aDC33.4b.V49 2018eb 7aHIS0130002bisacsh 7aHIS0370502bisacsh04a305.5/520944090332231 aVila, Anne C., eauthor.10aSuffering Scholars :bPathologies of the Intellectual in Enlightenment France /cAnne C. Vila. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource   atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aIntellectual History of the Modern Age00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Abbreviations -- tIntroduction -- t1. Medicine and the Cult of the Thinker, 1750-89 -- t2. The Ardor for Study: Inwardness and the Zealous Cerebralist -- t3. Passions and the Philosophe -- t4. Corporality and the Life of the Mind in Voltaire and Diderot -- t5. Melancholy, Genius, and Intellectual Identity: The Cases of Rousseau and Stael -- t6. Refashioning Intellectual Pathologies in the Wake of the Revolution -- tEpilogue. Not So Singular, After All? -- tNotes -- tBibliography of Primary Sources -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments  aAs early as Aristotle's Problem XXX, intellectual superiority has been linked to melancholy. The association between sickness and genius continued to be a topic for discussion in the work of early modern writers, most recognizably in Robert Burton's The Anatomy of Melancholy. But it was not until the eighteenth century that the phenomenon known as the "suffering scholar" reached its apotheosis, a phenomenon illustrated by the popularity of works such as Samuel-Auguste Tissot's De la santé des gens de lettres, first published in 1768. Though hardly limited to French-speaking Europe, the link between mental endeavor and physical disorder was embraced with particular vigor there, as was the tendency to imbue intellectuals with an aura of otherness and detachment from the world. Intellectuals and artists were portrayed as peculiarly susceptible to altered states of health as well as psyche-the combination of mental intensity and somatic frailty proved both the privileges and the perils of knowledge-seeking and creative endeavor.In Suffering Scholars, Anne C. Vila focuses on the medical and literary dimensions of the cult of celebrity that developed around great intellectuals during the French Enlightenment. Beginning with Tissot's work, which launched a subgenre of health advice aimed specifically at scholars, she demonstrates how writers like Voltaire, Diderot, Rousseau, and Mme de Staël, responded to the "suffering scholar" syndrome and helped to shape it. She traces the ways in which this syndrome influenced the cultural perceptions of iconic personae such as the philosophe, the solitary genius, and the learned lady. By showing how crucial the so-called suffering scholar was to debates about the mind-body relation as well as to sex and sensibility, Vila sheds light on the consequences book-learning was thought to have on both the individual body and the body politic, not only in the eighteenth century but also into the decades following the Revolution.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Sep 2018) 0aEnlightenmentzFrance. 0aIntellectualsxHealth and hygienezFrancexHistoryy18th century. 0aIntellectualsxHealth and hygienezFrancexHistoryy19th century. 0aIntellectualszFrancexHistoryy18th century. 4aCultural Studies. 4aEuropean History. 4aHistory. 4aLiterature. 4aWorld History.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018 Englishz978311060425208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018